the government says it plans to end its 
26yearold monopoly on television allowing two private channels 
to operate alongside the two existing official channels 
the new channels which should begin operating in the summer of 
1992 will still be closely regulated government spokesman luis 
marques mendes said thursday 
the government will control the length of airtime reserved for 
news educational shows and other programming marques mendes said 
the centerright government of prime minister anibal cavaco 
silva on thursday said prospective broadcasters will have three 
months from jan 2 to present their plans and two will be chosen in 
june or july 
a reform of the portuguese constitution in july 1989 allowed the 
government to end the monopoly of the staterun radiotelevisao 
portuguesa rtp 
initial enthusiasm for the project among portuguese and foreign 
businessmen has been dampened by recent studies casting doubt on 
the local advertizing markets capacity to support four channels 
