state officials have moved to make massachusetts 
safer for plants animals and people with laws ordering protection 
of wildlife habitat and a drastic reduction in automobile air 
pollution 
the measures were signed thursday by gov michael dukakis who 
leaves office next week 
the wildlife measure provides protection to more than 200 
threatened species of plants animals and invertebrates by 
controlling the alteration of wetlands and other areas where the 
wildlife reside 
this is the most important environmental legislation for 
wildlife ever passed in the commonwealth said christopher leahy 
the massachusetts audubon societys conservation director 
he said the legislation was controversial because it could limit 
what some private landowners can do on their property 
but its crucial to be able to truly protect things he 
said 
the new law also establishes a process for listing species as 
endangered threatened or of special concern and prohibits the 
taking or selling of those that make the list 
also thursday dukakis signed a clean air bill that goes beyond 
new federal requirements in restricting auto emissions 
the measure is based on standards recently adopted in 
california and supporters say it makes massachusetts only the 
second state to establish pollution controls stricter than the 
federal governments 
we hope to create a domino effect said jenny carter of the 
massachusetts public interest research group 
massachusetts air quality failed to meet federal health 
standards on at least 40 days over the past three summers this 
law will help reverse that trend carter said 
the law orders automobile manufacturers to cut smogcausing 
hydrocarbon and nitrogen oxide emissions from 50 percent to 75 
percent beyond what is required by the federal clean air act 
the law calls for the new emission standards to be phased in 
beginning in 1993 
manufacturers can meet the standards using any technology they 
wish but carter said she expects most manufacturers would refine 
catalytic converters to reduce more emissions 
she estimated the measure would cost consumers an extra 170 
when they buy a new car 
