<TEXT>
millions of dollars in federal funds provided 
to the states to fight the war against drugs are going unspent the 
office of national drug control policy says 
states have been spending just twothirds of their federal 
grants aimed at fighting drugs over the last four years the white 
house agency said thursday 
the situation is most striking for law enforcement grants where 
states have spent only 40 percent of the federal money they have 
received said bruce carnes director of planning budget and 
administration for the drug policy office 
i think whats bringing the spending level down is the law 
enforcement grant because there were such enormous increases in 
that in the last two years said carnes who released the figures 
as his office issued a report on block grants given to states over 
the past few years 
antidrug block grants issued by the justice department dropped 
from 178 million in the 1987 fiscal year to a low of 56 million 
in 1988 they jumped back to 119 million in 1989 before zooming to 
395 million in fiscal 1990 which ended sept 30 they climb to 
423 million this year 
theres going to be a huge wave of money carnes said it 
started to descend on them in 89 and 90 and its going to keep 
going up this year 
carnes said states spent 82 percent of their drug treatment and 
prevention grants 46 percent of their drug education grants and 40 
percent of their law enforcement grants 
overall the three block grant programs sent 5 billion to the 
states from october 1986 through june 1990 
only 34 billion or 68 percent of that amount was distributed 
during that time by state and territorial governments to antidrug 
programs the figures show 
obviously id like to see it higher but im not prepared to 
say theyre not doing their jobs carnes said 
among the states topranked arizona spent 834 percent of the 
777 million it received second was nevada spending 79 percent 
of 267 million followed by the us territories which spent 77 
percent of 633 million 
trailing the list puerto rico spent only 342 percent of the 
317 million it received hawaii spent 52 percent of 274 million 
and wyoming 55 percent of 141 million 
hawaii attorney general warren price said county prosecutors and 
police departments in the state use county funds for antidrug 
efforts and later seek reimbursement from the federal grants he 
said this sets up a time lag that makes it look as if the federal 
funds arent being spent quickly 
the drug policy office said in the report that it opposes giving 
such grants directly to cities on grounds that doing so would place 
too heavy a paperwork and administrative burden on the federal 
government 
instead of speeding up the process the time required at the 
federal level to review thousands of applications from local 
governments would almost certainly slow it down it said in the 
report 
states are closer to the problem than federal administrators 
and can more quickly react to changes in local requirements it 
added 
governors oppose giving the money directly to cities but mayors 
complain that the states fail to send the money to the places that 
need it the most 
