<TEXT>
pehlad singh a farmer in this small 
village in northern india is fighting a battle against an 
amusement park 
seven centuries ago singhs ancestors fought the moslem emperor 
balban when he tried and eventually succeeded to take over 
their area 
now singh and his fellow villagers want to stop roller coasters 
and lagoons from being built on their ancestral lands 
they say the park which is popularly called disneyland but 
has no connection with the real one in california will destroy 
their source of livelihood and ruin their culture 
the government wants to take our land and drive us out 
singh said we have warned them that rivers of blood will flow if 
they touch our land 
the confrontation began early this year when the government of 
the northern state of haryana announced plans to build indias 
first big amusement park on 28000 acres of land inhabited and 
farmed by 150000 people in 28 villages the government said the 
park would cost an estimated 555 million 
but the villagers mostly small farmers and cattle grazers said 
the government was trying to uproot them 
chief minister om prakash chautala haryanas highest elected 
official pushed the project through despite the peoples 
resistance 
even before disneyland chautalas name was synonymous with 
dynastic rule and corruption for many people 
villagers accused chautala of using the amusement park to push 
up land prices they said chautala and his friends had bought a lot 
of the surrounding land which would appreciate enormously once the 
amusement park was built 
haryanas tourism minister siri krishan hooda dismissed all 
these allegations as baseless 
the peoples fears were aggravated further last month when 
chautalas father devi lal became indias deputy prime minister 
and tourism minister 
chautala succeeded his father as haryanas chief minister last 
winter but was forced out of office by political infighting at the 
national level and the killings of at least 12 people when he ran 
for the state legislature but his father retains the political 
clout to expedite the disneyland project 
in december devi lal met the villagers and told them he would 
give the goahed for the project prime minister chandra shekhar 
who accompanied devi lal said he supported the project and wanted 
to see it through 
this is all nonsense said khem chand a 60yearold retired 
soldier who lives in one of the villages that would be supplanted 
by the amusement park instead of providing us education and 
basic health care the government is offering us amusement 
like many towns none of the 28 villages in this area 25 miles 
southwest of new delhi has sufficient drinking water the nearest 
hospital is several miles away and is usually filled to capacity 
the government is legally right but morally wrong said 
amrit singh a village headman they say they have no money to 
spare for village development but have enough for this useless 
project 
singhs lament and that of many others strikes at the heart 
of indias most pressing problem how to develop an overpopulated 
country of 880 million plagued by illiteracy and poverty without 
alienating the people 
the amusement park is not a need of the people said prem 
chowdhry a historian and a native of haryana its an example of 
development that leaves people out 
the haryana government doesnt agree it says it will pay the 
villagers 5555 an acre for their land and will employ them in the 
amusement park 
but the money offered by the government is several times lower 
than the market price india has a huge black market economy that 
pushes up the price of land enormously if the villagers sold their 
land to businessmen they could get between 27777 and 55555 an 
acre 
but the state government has frozen all land sales in the 
villages 
the villagers are also wary of the governments guarantee of 
employment they say the government seldom employs local people in 
tourist resorts two years ago the government held out a similar 
promise when it built a motel in damdama it hired four villagers 
but fired them within a week 
many villagers say they will not be able to put the money the 
government gives them to good use 
we have been farmers for generations and have never handled 
large sums of money said dhoom mahase a 42yearold farmer 
too much money will only destroy us 
