<TEXT>
the conservative government announced 
friday it intends to pardon nearly all the imprisoned leaders of 
the 196774 rightwing dictatorship 
the announcement to free seven of the eight former military 
leaders outraged socialists communists and other leftists 
thousands of whom were jailed or exiled during the dictatorship 
many politicians and other citizens were tortured 
andreas papandreou whose socialist government ruled from 1981 
to 1989 denounced the decision as an insult to those that fought 
and died for democracy in our country 
prime minister constantine mitsotakis proposed the pardon for 
humanitarian reasons after meeting with president constantine 
caramanlis justice minister athanassios kanellopoulos said the 
ministrys pardons committee will discuss it monday and approval 
was expected 
according to practice a pardon is proposed by the government 
and approved by the committee clearing the way for a presidential 
decree 
eight members of the junta are serving prison terms ranging from 
20 years to life imprisonment for their involvement in the military 
coup since their sentencing by a special court in 1975 they have 
refused to apply for pardons 
the only junta member left out of the proposed pardon was 
dimitris ioannides who engineered a failed 1974 coup in nearby 
cyprus a disaster that led to the partition of the mediterranean 
island and greeces return to civilian rule 
those serving life sentences include former col george 
papadopoulos 71 who led the april 1967 army coup in greece his 
brother constantine 69 and ioannides 67 a former brigadier who 
in turn overthrew papadopoulos they were originally sentenced to 
death for high treason 
the rest of those jailed are former military officers convicted 
of torture 
the military took over the government in 1967 following a period 
of political instability and papadopolous vowed at the time 
there is no possibility of democracy as practiced in the past 
ever returning to greece 
the junta was condemned in the west as clumsy and authoritarian 
its political opponents were tortured by the military police and 
exiled by the thousands to barren greek islands 
the united states distanced itself from the junta and 
temporarily banned arms sales to greece but thenvice president 
spiro agnew went to greece in 1971 in a visit seen a tacit approval 
of the regime 
the junta relinquished power after a student uprising in 
november 1973 and ioannides failed 1974 coup in cyprus aimed at 
uniting the island with greece 
the shortlived coup resulted in turkey invading the island 
ostensibly to protect the turkishcypriot minority the july 1974 
invasion of cyprus brought greece and turkey to the brink of war 
the military turned over power latr that year to an interim 
government led by caramanlis which oversaw elections caramanlis 
also had immediately commuted the death sentences handed down by 
the special court 
six other members of the junta have been released over the years 
for health reasons 
papandreou the main opposition leader said the governments 
decision to pardon the junta members would allow them to claim 
their 1967 military coup was justified 
it is a case of justification they didnt ask for a pardon 
it was imposed on them from above papandreou said 
the communistdominated coalition of the left and progress said 
it considered the government decision an insult to the democratic 
feelings of the greek people 
mitsotakis conservative new democracy returned to power in 
april after losing to the socialists in 1981 the prime minister 
said caramanlis did not have any objections to his decision 
</TEXT>
