about 80 warplanes from the norfolk naval base in virginia 
they will join three other carriers in the area the uss 
saratoga in the eastern mediterranean the uss midway in the 
arabian sea and the uss kennedy in the red sea 
the fresh troops will bring the united states closer to its goal 
of having about 430000 in saudi arabia and nearby waters to 
confront iraq if it refuses to withdraw from kuwait by jan 15 
the deadline imposed by the united nations 
meanwhile the pentagon said it was preparing to inoculate 
troops against possible germ warfare by iraq 
we are committed to providing maximum protection for our 
troops including protection against chemical and biological 
weapons said a brief statement we expect to begin a program 
of inoculations soon it said but did not provide further 
detail 
the new york times which first reported the plan said the 
inoculations could begin in a matter of weeks it also said the 
united states doesnt yet have sufficient vaccines for all its 
troops in the gulf 
in london the british defense ministry said british troops 
taking part in operation desert shield also would receive 
inoculations the ministry said it was issuing gas masks to about 
british 21000 civilians in the area 
britain is contributing about 21000 troops to the antiiraq 
force 
in other developments friday iraq test fired a 
surfacetosurface missile for the second time this week the us 
central command in saudi arabia reported that the missle was fired 
away from multinational forces and that it landed within iraq 
military analysts also said that thousands of iraqis have been 
trained for suicide attacks on the usled forces if war breaks 
out 
cia director william webster has said in recent weeks that iraq 
has sizable stockpiles of biological weapons iraq denied the 
allegations 
biological weapons are basically germs viruses and bacteria 
that cause diseases such as cholera anthrax typhoid botulism 
they can be delivered by warheads on missiles by lowflying planes 
spreading the germs much like a crop duster or by contamination of 
water supplies 
unlike nuclear or even chemical arms biological weapons are 
easy to make because they rely on the kind of agents and equipment 
used in manufacturing pharmaceuticals and are readily available on 
world markets 
the us commerce department for example approved more than 20 
shipments of biological agents to the iraqi government according 
to a congressional staffer investigating the sales the us 
company which sold the agents believed they would be used for 
vaccinations said the official 
defenses against germ warfare include protective clothing 
masks and vaccines 
experts caution however that dozens of diseases can be 
converted into weapons making it hard to know against which to 
inoculate 
also it could take one month or longer to develop immunity to 
some of the diseases after being vaccinated said dr sanford 
kuvin vice chairman of the national foundation for infectious 
diseases 
one of the diseases iraq is believed to have in its arsenal is 
anthrax an easily transmittable and severely incapacitating 
illness 
the vaccine however is not commercially available because the 
only people who need it in this country are those handling imported 
raw hides and goat hair 
the vaccine is only made by michigans public health lab which 
is having trouble keeping up with the demands for gulf troops 
newsweek reported 
another disease iraqi president saddam hussein is known to have 
in his arsenal is botulism a form of stomach poisoning which is 
treatable with antibiotics but against which there is no vaccine 
the united states wasnt the only nation gearing up for a 
possible fight 
in london the government ordered the callup of 390 medical 
reservists for service in the gulf after getting too few 
volunteers the british are members of the antiiraq coalition 
and to prevent being stranded by war more than 250 soviet 
citizens left iraq friday and 1000 others were to be evacuated by 
jan 10 soviet deputy premier igor belousov met with officials in 
baghdad seeking to terminate numerous commercial contracts with 
iraq 
but japanese prime minister toshiki kaifu urged talks with iraq 
on averting war 
the state department said however that there hadnt been any 
progress in efforts to arrange a meeting between secretary of state 
james baker and saddam iraq wants jan 12 as the meeting date but 
baker says he wont go after jan 3 
for the second day in a row the senior us diplomat in 
baghdad joseph c wilson did not have any contact with the iraqi 
foreign ministry said mark dillen a state department spokesman 
</TEXT>
