albanias communist government legalized 
the first opposition newspaper on friday and announced greater 
independence for television and other news media the state news 
agency ata reported 
in a dispatch monitored in vienna ata said the council of 
ministers decided to allow the democratic party to publish a 
newspaper and to make directors of ata and of official television 
and radio responsible to the state indicating the communist party 
would have less direct control 
an official journalist reached by telephone in the capital of 
tirana said communistsponsored directors would probably keep their 
posts for the moment 
the ministers also decided to set up a commission to draft a 
news media law for approval by parliament after feb 10 elections 
ata said 
up to now there was no law regulating the media i understand 
this move to mean more independence from the party the 
journalist said speaking on condition of anonymity 
president ramiz alia has sped up political reform since student 
protests over dormitory conditions this month grew into demands for 
democracy in albania europes last holdout for hardline 
communism 
the communists in power since 1944 still control nearly all 
spheres of public life including the media 
gramoz pashko a cofounder of the recently legalized democratic 
party said fridays decision meant the planned newspaper rilindja 
demokratika or democratic revival would go to press in the next 
day or two 
he said in a telephone interview that the democrats held a rally 
friday in the central city of elbasan their second rally outside 
tirana and estimated that 35000 people attended 
pashko reported no police interference and no incidents 
he said the government authorized use of stateowned presses at 
a fee to print the paper a first edition of 100000 is planned to 
be distributed around albania by students and other supporters for 
a one lek 10cent cover price he added 
pashko said the paper would also be sold to albanian communities 
in neighboring yugoslavia and elsewhere abroad we shall cover 
the costs and by selling abroad raise funds for the party 
the price for the eightpage paper was three times that of the 
communist party daily zeri i popullit 
an electoral law adopted before the democratic party was 
legalized forbids political parties to receive foreign funding 
but pashko said raising funds through newspaper sales was legal 
four decrees by the council of ministers on friday were all 
signed by premier adil carcani 
one says newspapers would not be allowed to publish articles 
calling for overthrow of the constitutional order or other 
destabilizing acts said an albanian radio report monitored by 
the british broadcasting corp 
