prosecutors showed him 35 volumes of files relating to the 1940 
katyn massacre including such details as schedules for trains that 
carried the prisoners 
after 47 years of denials the soviet government in april 
admitted responsibility for the murders which it had previously 
blamed on the nazis on dec 18 polish prosecutors were allowed 
their first look at the documents sniezko said 
a total of 4254 polish prisoners including the cream of the 
polish intelligentsia and 800 doctors were executed and stacked in 
mass graves by the soviet secret police in the katyn forest near 
the city of smolensk 
the bodies were found by german troops moving east through 
russia in 1943 
but until the current investigation the whereabouts of an 
additional 10000 poles who were interned in camps at starobielsk 
and ostashkov northwest of moscow had been a mystery 
sniezko said that the soviet military prosecutors who took over 
the case in october after the personal intervention of president 
mikhail s gorbachev hoped to chart the fate of each victim 
