<TEXT>
in its brief heyday it was a place 
where people would go to browse for antiques or enjoy a night on 
the town 
but for the last 13 years ever since a series of mob bombings 
and gangland slayings closed taverns and scared customers away 
kansas citys river quay area has sat deserted 
transients slept beside empty buildings and an xrated movie 
theater the only sign of a former era came on saturday mornings 
when produce companies sold vegetables and fruit out of dilapidated 
stalls 
now with 40 million in public and private investment and a new 
name the citys river market area hopes to draw people back with a 
renovated produce market upscale loft apartments quaint 
restaurants shops and a riverboat museum 
its the kind of restoration that has led to a business and 
economic surge for historic commercial areas in many cities from 
bostons faneuil hall marketplace to fishermans wharf in san 
francisco 
were trying to create a neighborhood to have people living 
down here and shopping down here and were finally starting to 
show some results said bette guarino president of a nonprofit 
group that struggled for years to find a private company to develop 
the area 
people with organized crime connections no longer own property 
in the area which lies just north of downtown and south of the 
missouri river ms guarino said the mob cant move in this time 
because of tighter city zoning controls she said developers are 
focusing on restaurants and apartments not bars 
but others say the river quays legacy lingers 
when its finished itll be the greatest thing that ever 
happened to this city said mary jane orlando the owner of mama 
orlandos restaurant one of the few eateries open in the area 
more are scheduled to open soon 
but its not finished yet mrs orlando said people are 
watching whats going on down here theyre aware of the progress 
but theyre still scared 
mrs orlando said she got a typical reaction during a recent 
trip to a dentist in a northern kansas city suburb 
when i gave the address of my place of business the 
receptionist who id never met looked at me and said arent you 
scared to be down there with the mafia mrs orlando said so a 
lot of people are still thinking about that 
in the last year the area has regained some of its former 
charm the private development company that bought many of the 
areas old buildings has leased more than 70 loft apartments to 
young professionals and couples many of whom work downtown 
another developer owns two buildings full of loft apartments where 
poets hold public readings on weekend nights 
the city has repaved streets and put in new lights brick 
sidewalks and trees this spring a museum housing a restored 
paddlewheel from a riverboat that sank in 1856 is scheduled to 
open 
the physical renovation is going really great said brian 
collins president of the economic development corp we have a 
lot of hopes for it in other cities this kind of market area has 
really sparked revivals 
the area evolved slowly from a stretch of river shorline into a 
a business district and farmers market the brother of tom 
pendergast a famous political boss once owned a tavern there but 
it was mostly warehouses by the time a local developer got the idea 
to attract artists and restaurants in 1972 
a year after the first shops and artists lofts opened 60 
businesses were operating but a surprisingly high number were 
bars as the area prospered the mob mucled in attempting to 
transform it into a redlight district 
then arson fires started the father of one bar owner who 
resisted mob intimidation was found slain in a car trunk other 
slayings followed artists moved away and customers stopped coming 
there was a time when i had to defend this project everywhere 
i went and everyone i talked to because of all that history ms 
guarino said i still run across that a little but not nearly as 
much now people want to know whats happening 
