<TEXT>
the closer 1991 gets the dicier it looks to wall 
street analysts trying to sort out prospects for the economy and 
corporate profits 
the news on business activity has grown gloomier and gloomier in 
the waning weeks of 1990 challenging widespread hopes in the 
financial world that the economy might face nothing worse than a 
short and shallow recession 
the portents for the near future dont offer much consolation 
on friday the commerce department reported a fifth consecutive 
monthly decline in the index of leading economic indicators 
many forecasters also lament that the special characteristics of 
the current slump make its dangers hard to gauge 
in most downturns of the past few decades recessions ran their 
course as businesses were able to work down inventories that had 
built up in booming inflationary periods 
now most observers agree the prime source of trouble lies not 
in production and distribution but rather in finance 
specifically the accumulated debts of the past decade or more 
in the absence of much recent precedent analysts say it is 
tough to calculate how long it might take or how much pain will be 
required to complete the process of debt retrenchment 
the need to reliquify after a decade of debt accumulation 
should be the overriding force in the years ahead said jack 
lavery director of global research at merrill lynch 
the economy will likely remain in recession until the second 
half of 1991 the recession is likely to be about average in length 
and severity with direction of risk on the weaker and more 
protracted side 
we hate to be skeptical adds robert nurock a paoli pa 
investment advisor 
however we see little evidence that the economy is close to 
bottoming in fact we believe that most of the recently released 
data implies that the decline is accelerating 
amid such misgivings stock prices drifted lower in the past 
week in extremely light activity surrounding the christmas holiday 
the dow jones average of 30 industrials dropped 445 to 262921 
the new york stock exchange composite index fell 122 to 17965 
the nasdaq composite index for the overthecounter market dropped 
241 to 37120 and the american stock exchange market value index 
was down 155 at 30465 
volume on the big board averaged only 8747 million shares a 
day down from 17670 million the week before 
even if the recession as it is ultimately defined by 
economists turns out to be relatively mild many analysts worry 
that the ensuing recovery could be slow and painful 
once the us economy emerges from the recession or 
nearrecession we expect sluggish growth for years to come 
gerald rothstein at oppenheimer amp co told the firms clients 
overall growth will be hampered by the hangover from 
privatesector leverage and the need for private funds to be used 
to fund the federal deficit and the savings and loan and perhaps 
banking crisis 
or as analysts at the firm of griggs amp santow put it this 
slowdown has its origins in the excesses of the 1980s 
specifically the decision by all sectors of the economy to greatly 
expand their debts and to take greater risks 
all these activities were largely financed by institutions 
that now find themselves the notsoproud owners of real estate and 
securities that are under water 
the real estate and junkbond markets face problems now that go 
well beyond any questions of federal reserve policy or the level of 
interest rates the firm asserts 
thus look for the fed recognizing the nature of this 
downturn to move cautiously despite its recent aggressiveness 
and for the economy to recover from this downturn very slowly 
