<TEXT>
the nations only law regulating video 
display terminal use was signed thursday by mayor art agnos who 
touted the ordinance as being on the cutting edge of social 
change 
the law covers city workers and businesses with 15 or more 
employees 
it requires employers to provide adjustable work stations 
regular breaks and training on safe use of vdts the law also 
recommends that pregnant vdt users be shifted to other work if they 
request it 
employers would have been given two years to make the changes 
but a compromise worked out last weekend between agnos and business 
and labor leaders gives employers four years to comply 
this legislation will ensure san francisco workers are 
protected from dangerous injury without driving away businesses 
agnos said its legislation on the cutting edge of social 
change 
one voice raised against the measure is that of tom hsieh a 
member of the board of supervisors who contends it violates the 
city charter legal authorities in city hall say hes wrong 
a similar ordinance passed in 1988 in suffolk county on new 
yorks long island and bitterly opposed by business owners was 
overturned a year later by a state court on the grounds the local 
government lacked authority to make such rules that decision is 
under appeal 
the san francisco legislation was pushed by a coalition of 
activists who cited potential risks to vdt operators including 
repetitive strain injury back and neck pain deteriorating vision 
and miscarriage 
hsieh said the city charter prohibits supervisors from changing 
working conditions for city employees without studies by the civil 
service commission jonathan holtzman special assistant in the 
city attorneys office said the provision only applies to changes 
in pay not safety measures 
the law will affect an estimated 56000 workers in its first 30 
months it will cost businesses about 14 million said paul 
varacalli executive director of service employees international 
union local 590 which backed the measure 
he estimated the cost of bringing the city into compliance at 
231552 
the 11member board of supervisors is to vote next month on the 
compromise program of compliance 
under the program new equipment would have to meet standards 
set in the ordinance after one year for existing work stations 
retrofitting costing less than 250 would have to be completed 
within 30 months retrofitting costing more than 250 would have to 
be completed within four years 
the compromise was reached after business and labor officials 
said time constraints in the ordinance were unacceptable 
we hope that careful administration of this ordinance provides 
something we all can live with said gwen kaplan president of 
the san francisco small business association at best its a 
first step toward longrange solutions 
varacalli said the push to provide legal guarantees for vdt 
safety wont end in san francisco 
we know it cannot stop here this is the beginning we had to 
have a beginning he said 
