<TEXT>
eighteen directors of mazda motor corp are 
voluntarily taking temporary pay cuts to impress upon employees the 
seriousness of a government warning to pay stricter attention to 
car safety 
in japan there is an old saying that superiors must suffer 
first in order to motivate workers mazda spokesman tetsuo nagase 
said thursday explaining the action announced a day earlier 
mazda said wednesday that chairman kenichi yamamoto and 17 other 
directors would take a pay cut of 5 percent to 10 percent in the 
first three months of 1991 in connection with a recall of nearly 
3500 cars 
the pay cuts were decided after the transport ministry 
investigating charges that mazda has been replacing defective parts 
during routine maintenance without recalling the cars or notifying 
the government warned the company to pay stricter attention to 
safety 
after the warning mazda notified the ministry tuesday it would 
recall 3498 luce model passenger cars produced between aug 8 
1986 and jan 31 1987 because of switch defects in their stop 
lights and cruise control mechanisms 
nagase said the directors pay cut has a very symbolic meaning 
and employees will realize it we believe cutting directors 
salaries is a more effective way of having workers realize the 
importance of the matter than cutting workers pay 
he also said it would have been very unjapanese to try to 
pinpoint an individual or department for blame 
pinpointing who is responsible and firing him would not solve 
the problem nagase said 
hajime karatsu a professor at the research and development 
institute of tokai university said that whenever something goes 
wrong for japanese corporations the first move is for directors to 
take salary cuts 
in extreme cases business and political leaders offer their 
resignations in a recent example the chairman of sumitomo bank 
stepped down to take responsibility for illegal loans allegedly 
arranged by a branch manager for stock manipulation 
all the responsibility should be placed with managers thats 
the way of thinking in japan karatsu said 
he said actions such as executive pay cuts were a modern form of 
harakiri the ritual suicide by disembowelment practiced by 
highranking japanese to avoid disgrace 
but spokesman nagase said mazda did not view the government 
warning as a matter for which the company needed to take 
responsibility he said mazda broke no laws and violated no 
regulations 
we and our president have acknowledged that our judgment was a 
bit shortsighted he said 
he said company officials told the ministry that mazda will try 
to streamline its quality check systems 
