those figures reflect companies diminished ability and desire 
to raise money by selling shares to the public hayes said that as 
stock prices dropped in 1990 corporations balked at selling what 
would have amounted to cheap shares 
wall street firms serve as intermediaries for stock and bond 
offerings they acquire the securities from companies and then 
resell them to the public charging a fee for the service 
raising money by offering debt in the form of corporate bonds 
rose by 36 percent in 1990 to 2825 billion idd reported but 
