with domestic firms for us deals also the growth of practices 
such as shelf underwriting in which a company opens the 
bidding among investment firms for a deal have driven down fee 
commissions 
theres just been an absolute compression on fees because of 
intense competition hilderman said 
not all of wall streets losses are due to the decline in 
underwriting fees other key areas for big investment banks also 
fell sharply in 1990 particularly mergers and acquisitions fees 
and takeoverstock speculation 
securities firms are cutting back to stanch losses they are 
