<TEXT>
canadas stateowned nuclear power 
company signed a 535 million us contract friday to build a 
nuclear power plant for korea electric power corp 
the deal is a coup for the canadian government and caps more 
than 10 years of sales efforts by its atomic energy of canada ltd 
or aecl it will be the second canadian reactor built in korea 
officials said the 700000kilowatt power plant estimated to 
cost a total of about 1 billion us will be built in wolsong 
160 miles southeast of seoul it will be built next to the first 
canadian reactor which has been operating since 1983 
were ecstatic said william b schumacher the canadian 
ambassador to south korea a deal of this size has implications 
for bilateral relations it opens up a basis for broadening even 
further the relationship 
south korea and canada are each others fifthlargest trading 
partners trade between the companies is expected to reach 4 
billion us in 1990 
the korean power company or kepco has nine nuclear power 
plants in operation and two more under construction the government 
expects to have 50 nuclear plants in operation in the next 40 
years 
a nuclear reactor provides heat that converts water into steam 
the steam is then fed from the reactor into a turbine system to 
convert into electricity 
schumacher said south korea is the only country using two 
complementary kinds of nuclear reactors a heavywater reactor 
developed by canada and the more commonly used pressure water 
reactors 
the canadian model uses natural uranium and heavy water that 
means the socalled candu reactor can use the spent fuel from 
pressurewater reactors enabling korea to reduce the amount of 
nuclear waste it generates experts said 
the sale should also prove beneficial to aecl it is the 
companys first in nine years and could provide a boost to canadas 
nuclear industry 
a turbine generator for the new plant will be supplied by 
general electric co along with korea heavy industries and 
construction co under a contract to be signed soon officials 
said 
aecl will receive about 60 percent of the total contract sum 
korean subcontractors will receive the other 40 percent for 
providing components and services kepco said 
construction will begin next july and is scheduled to be 
completed by mid1997 
the contract was formally signed at a ceremony friday by ahn 
byongwha president of kepco and dr stanley hatcher of toronto 
president of aecl 
