<TEXT>
when talks at the worlds major trade forum 
collapsed earlier this month experts and headlines echoed each 
other in handwringing dismay over the loss of a chance to set 
visionary rules for the 21st century 
but not all agree the consequences of a breakdown would be dire 
a small but vocal group of experts argues that the general 
agreement on tariffs and trade is at best imbalanced further 
some say the world is becoming so economically interdependent that 
trade will increase exponentially in coming decades even without a 
broader agreement 
we might end up having a thoroughly free trading world because 
it is imposed by economic realities rather than policymakers and 
politicians says world trade expert dominick salvatore of 
fordham university in new york 
even without a gatt agreement bilateral trade talks will 
continue us and japanese negotiators for example have 
continued talks under the structural impediments initiative aimed 
at reducing internal barriers to trade in their countries us 
agriculture secretary clayton k yeutter visited european community 
counterpart ray macsharry a few weeks ago to discuss trade 
the latest gatt talks launched four years ago in uruguay were 
suspended dec 7 in brussels after the united states and other 
agricultural exporters demanded deep cuts in agricultural subsidies 
a politically explosive issue in the 12 ec nations and japan 
where farmers form strong political blocs 
the talks aim to overhaul the world trade system by rewriting 
rules and lowering barriers in 15 areas including textiles 
agriculture manufactured goods and services such as banking 
telecommunications and construction 
us negotiators hope that if developing nations gain markets 
for their food exports they will in turn grant concessions in the 
newer areas the gatt doesnt cover financial services high 
technology and socalled intellectual property such as patents 
and copyrights all of which most analysts agree hold the highest 
potential for future growth in developed nations 
when the 107nation talks were halted some feared the end of 
the pact credited with slashing barriers to trade since the gatt 
was signed in 1947 global trade has increased over five times in 
real terms to about 4 trillion in 1990 
there is still hope for gatt the talks could resume as early as 
january and a deadline set by congress of march 1 1991 to vote 
on a world trade treaty can easily be extended two years at 
president bushs request the next two months will probably 
decide it said julius katz deputy united states trade 
representative 
but salvatore and others argue that the gatt is offbase 
anyway they say that the united states naively cajoles other 
nations to hold to fair trade principles but those countries 
arent even convinced laissezfaire capitalism is best for them 
my concern is its the wrong fight at the wrong place at the 
wrong time salvatore says the future lies not in 
agricultureit is in high technology 
even if gatt succeeds it may not bring the huge trade flows 
negotiators are promising 
clyde v prestowitz and robert w jerome of the economic 
strategy institute in washington disparage a us estimate that a 
new gatt agreement could bring an extra 1 trillion in trade over 
the next decade 
bemoaning the fate of the uruguay round is kind of misplaced 
because no matter what came out of that round we the united 
states were going to have problems says prestowitz president 
of esi 
prestowitz and jerome say that under the current system the more 
liberal trading nations lose 
under current national treatment and mostfavorednation 
rules a gatt country must treat other members the same way it 
treats businesses at home no matter how restrictive a countrys 
home policies it can take advantage of more liberal members 
internal rules say jerome and prestowitz 
prestowitz a former us commerce department official cites 
european government backing for the airbus airliner 
the europeans have been pursuing development of the airbus for 
20 years subsidized to the tune of about 28 billion he says 
were not losing market share because our planes are bad or our 
prices too high were losing it because were being 
outsubsidized 
