<TEXT>
the difficult christmas season has ended but 
many of the nations retailers are finding it hard to breathe a 
sigh of relief with the outlook poor for consumer spending in the 
first half of 1991 many still have tough sledding ahead 
as a result retailers are retrenching paring inventories and 
expenses and in some cases closing stores others in financial 
distress are expected to seek refuge in bankruptcy courts 
its going to be terrible was the way daniel barry a 
kidder peabody amp co industry analyst summed up the outlook 
the christmas season when retailers hope to make half their 
annual profits was disappointing as consumers put fears about the 
economy and the middle east ahead of holiday sentimentality 
the nations biggest retailers will report sales for the month 
of december on thursday but several already have said it was a 
dismal or at best trying season 
many economists predict consumers will spend cautiously well 
into 1991 as the recession continues that means americans will 
limit what is called discretionary spending outlays for 
nonessentials such as toys furniture appliances even clothing 
with retailers dependent on such expenditures a further 
slowdown is expected to be devastating for 1991 earnings thomas j 
tashjian an analyst with seidler amdec securities inc in los 
angeles predicted overall industry profits would fall about 30 
percent in the first quarter and 15 percent the second quarter 
even before christmas retailers were taking steps to reduce 
inventories and many have said they are trying to keep merchandise 
levels tight going into the new year 
we will continue to plan very conservatively kenneth macke 
chairman of dayton hudson corp said last week macke reported his 
christmas sales were unchanged to 1 percent higher than a year 
earlier a disappointing performance 
retailers especially apparel merchants will be taking fewer 
chances in 1991 
theyre going to choose very carefully things to sell said 
walter loeb a retail analyst and consultant theyre going to 
buy classic clothes which are safe 
some companies are taking more drastic steps one retailer 
younkers inc which owns 34 department stores in five midwestern 
states announced last week it was closing three small marginally 
profitable stores in nebraska 
its just a sound business decision company president 
thomas gould said 
others including such big names as rh macy amp co inc and 
carter hawley hale stores inc have already sold extra stock or 
some of their stores to try to reduce their debt loads 
macy got a 119 million cash infusin from a sale of stock 
earlier this month and has been buying back some of its junk bonds 
macy which had a disastrous christmas a year ago and has been 
under pressure to reduce its multibilliondollar liabilities 
fared better this holiday season according to a source familiar 
with the retailers results 
macys sales volume was not good in comparison to last year or 
to others in the recent past but because of lower inventories and 
reduced expenses our margins this christmas were well above a 
year ago said the source who spoke on condition of anonymity 
carter hawley hale which operates department stores in 
california and the west recently sold its thalhimer brothers 
division in the southeast to reduce its debt the company lost 
149 million in its first quarter which ended in november after 
losing 26 million the previous fiscal year 
for some retailers the recession will mean more business 
storeowners who can offer consumers the lowest prices should do 
well said tashjian 
closeout retailers such as pic n save corp who buy 
manufacturers overstock and sell the goods at a steep discount 
and discount retailers such as walmart stores inc are likely to 
fare better than competitors tashjian said 
walmarts sales gains consistently outpace those of other 
discounters because its distribution system is more modern and 
efficient tashjian said adding the company is in a position to 
have better pricing and still be profitable 
walmart said last week it was pleased with christmas results 
but the company found it difficult to draw customers 
some retailers are beginning the new year in bankruptcy court 
on friday youthland inc a columbus ohiobased chain of 26 
childrens clothing stores filed for protection from creditors 
under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code 
the retailer said it had lost money for seven consecutive 
quarters and blamed the losses on a heavy debt load poor locations 
for its stores and the economy 
analysts expect other bankruptcies largely among smaller 
privatelyheld retailers and companies that are overburdened by 
debt 
therell be hundreds of little firms that go out of business 
that youll never hear about barry said 
retail capital spending may also be a victim of the business 
slowdown with less money available from banks fewer shopping 
malls will be developed loeb predicted 
but at dayton hudson no major changes are planned in the 
companys capital spending plan macke said 
macke said he was looking pessimistically at business for the 
first part of 1991 noting that consumers traditionally spend more 
at christmas than any other time of the year 
