<TEXT>
wheelingpittsburgh steel corp on friday 
said it would take a 170 million onetime charge against 
fourthquarter earnings to adjust for retiree health benefits 
the charge includes 74 million in major medical insurance 
benefits for retirees granted in a labor contract signed dec 19 
spokesman ray thompson said 
it also includes 96 million for changes in retirees medical 
and life insurance benefits to update previous estimates of health 
coveage the company said in a news release 
wheelingpitt said the charge was required to show the companys 
expectations of medical costs and to reflect accounting changes 
the financial accounting standards board recently approved a new 
rule effective in 1993 that requires companies to subtract from 
earnings a portion of the costs of benefits they have promised to 
future retirees 
the change is designed to give investors and others a more 
accurate picture of a companys health by better stating what its 
longrange obligations to retirees will be 
meanwhile friday the company said a federal judge in pittsburgh 
had granted a temporary stay delaying the companys emergence from 
bankruptcy protection the stay was requested by the us 
environmental protection agency the economic development 
administration and farmers home administration 
wheelingpitt sought bankruptcy protection in 1985 and its 
reorganization plan had been approved dec 18 by the us 
bankruptcy court 
a hearing on the stay was scheduled for jan 3 
wheelingpitt the nations 10thlargest steel producer employs 
about 7100 workers at six plants in pennsylvania ohio and west 
virginia 
