<TEXT>
american airlines could be threatening passenger 
safety if pilots are discouraged from calling in sick or filing 
maintenance requests union officials said friday but the carrier 
called that statement hogwash 
the allied pilots association which represents americans 8000 
pilots has told members to obey a temporary restraining order 
against the illegal tactics that management alleges have caused 
delays and flight cancellations 
but pilots said the injunction granted wednesday by us 
district judge john mcbryde could jeopardize passenger safety if 
i is used to inhibit pilots from filing necessary maintenance 
requests and staying home when they are sick 
the clash over the court ruling is the latest in an increasingly 
testy struggle between american and its pilots who have been 
working without a contract for nearly a year mcbryde set a jan 3 
hearing date to determine whether the temporary injunction should 
be made permanent 
we pointed out to the court that there is a danger that the 
company may use the order in a way that will impair safe 
operations we cannot permit that to happen apa president fred 
vogel told pilots in a taped message on the unions telephone 
hotline 
the union has denied americans charges that pilots have been 
staging sickouts taxiing slowly to waste fuel and filing frivolous 
requests for equipment maintenance 
american spokeswoman lise olson said typically 300 pilots will 
call in sick on a given day but since dec 21 more than 500 a day 
have been out sick 
she said 204 flights had been canceled as of friday afternoon 
48 of which were crewrelated a snowstorm in the northeast caused 
most of the others she said 
ms olson said the airline never would compromise passenger 
safety 
thats hogwash its not our intention to endanger anyone 
olson said we would expect all of our employees to act 
professionally 
vogel said sick pilots could fail faaadministered drug tests if 
they are forced to work after taking certain overthecounter cold 
remedies he added that pilots will not be able to blame such an 
incident on the injunction 
you can bet your bottom dollar it will be the pilots who bear 
the responsibility if there is an incident vogel said 
the apa has been in contract talks since october 1989 the old 
contract expired jan 1 1990 
